-- Italian Stocks Advance; Fiat, Gemina, Mediaset, Prysmian, Saipem, UBI Move
-- Francesca Cinelli
-- 2010-07-08T15:44:33Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-08/as-roma-telecom-italia-unicredit-may-move-today-italian-equity-preview.html

          
          
             Italy’s benchmark  FTSE MIB Index  rose
for a third day, gaining 230.66, or 1.2 percent, to 20,243.73 in
Milan.  
 The following stocks are among the most active in the
Italian market today.  
 Azimut Holding SpA  (AZM IM), Italy’s largest independent
fund manager, rose 11.5 cents, or 1.7 percent, to 7.04 euro. The
Stoxx Europe 600 Index gained for a third day as the
International Monetary Fund raised its global growth forecast
and banks climbed on optimism stress tests will ease concern
about the health of the financial system.  
 Fiat SpA  (F IM) increased 17 cents, or 2 percent, to 8.72
euros. Gruppo Banca Leonardo reiterated a “buy” recommendation
on the Italian carmaker after Fiat brand Chief Executive Officer
Lorenzo Sistino said that Italian car sales are down about 19
percent in July.  
 “Should the trend be confirmed, the data is more positive
than the initial forecast of a market drop to 1.75 million units
for 2010 provided at the beginning of the year and included in
Fiat’s targets.”  
 Gemina SpA  (GEM IM), the owner of Rome’s airports operator,
advanced 1.2 cents, or 2.3 percent, to 53.4 cents, the highest
in about two weeks. Italy’s government infrastructure committee
CIPE may approve increases next week in fees that airport
companies charge airlines for services including take-off and
landing, MF reported, citing Transport Minister Altero Matteoli.  
 Intesa Sanpaolo SpA  (ISP IM) advanced 4.5 cents, or 1.9
percent, to 2.39 euros. Credit Suisse Group AG upgraded European
banks to “market weight” from “underweight.”  
 With regard to the stress tests, Banca Akros said in a note
that “at a European level, between 10 and 20 of the 91 banks
could fail to pass the hurdle of a Tier 1 ratio of 6 percent. We
do not expect any Italian bank to face this problem.”  
 Landi Renzo SpA  (LR IM) advanced 13.5 cents, or 4.4
percent, to 3.21 euros. UniCredit Research, which has a “buy”
rating on the maker of injection systems for alternative fuels,
said in a note that it “strongly believe consensus estimates
will rise in the coming weeks and months.”  
 Mediaset SpA  (MS IM) gained 15.25 cents, or 3.4 percent, to
4.67 euros, a third straight increase. Royal Bank of Scotland
Group Plc upgraded the stock to “buy” from “hold,” while
trimming its price estimate to 6 euros from 6.3 euros. Italy’s
advertising spending is forecast to rise 2 percent this year,
industry group UPA said in a statement handed to reporters in
Milan.  
 Prysmian SpA  (PRY IM) lost 25 cents, or 2 percent, to 12.28
euros as shares of the world’s second-biggest cable maker fell
below their 50-day moving average.  
 Saipem SpA  (SPM IM) increased 53 cent, or 2 percent, to
26.68 euros, a third day of gains. Europe’s largest oilfield-
services provider got offshore contracts for more than 1 billion
euros, according to a statement distributed by the Italian
exchange. The deals include the extension of a contract in
Kazakhstan, it said.  
 UniCredit SpA  (UCG IM) increased 2.4 cents, or 1.2 percent,
to 1.99 euros. Chief Executive Officer Alessandro Profumo said
Italy’s biggest bank “has no problem” with stress tests,
speaking to reporters in Rome today. UniCredit expects to pass
the stress tests, he said.  
 Unione di Banche Italiane ScpA  (UBI IM) climbed 18 cents,
or 2.3 percent, to 7.98 euros, the highest in about eight weeks,
as Equita Sim SpA lifted its recommendation to “buy” and added
the stock to its “main portfolio.”  
